{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Following modifications to production code, existing test cases may become obsolete or invalid.",
    "Studies such as Ceprot [29] and TaRGET [155] leverage fine-tuning or prompting techniques to empower LLMs to understand code changes (typically provided in diff format) and automatically transform old test cases into updated versions compatible with the modified code, thereby significantly alleviating the maintenance burden of regression testing [165].Finally, to enhance the engineering quality of tests, particularly readability and maintainability, LLMs are utilized to detect and repair test smells.",
    "LLM-generated tests frequently exhibit design flaws such as magic number test (hard-coded constants in assertions) and assertion foulette (multiple unexplained assertions within a single test method) [76,102,104].",
    "To address this issue, the UTRefactor framework [48] successfully eliminated 89% of test smells by combining domain-specific language (DSL) with CoT prompting.",
    "Other studies confirm that LLMs can be leveraged to automatically refactor obscure tests generated by traditional tools (e.g., EvoSuite) into maintainable code featuring meaningful variable names and comments [34,51]."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Studies such as Ceprot [29] and TaRGET [155] leverage fine-tuning or prompting techniques to empower LLMs to understand code changes (typically provided in diff format) and automatically transform old test cases into updated versions compatible with the modified code, thereby significantly alleviating the maintenance burden of regression testing [165].Finally, to enhance the engineering quality of tests, particularly readability and maintainability, LLMs are utilized to detect and repair test smells.",
    "LLM-generated tests frequently exhibit design flaws such as magic number test (hard-coded constants in assertions) and assertion foulette (multiple unexplained assertions within a single test method) [76,102,104].",
    "To address this issue, the UTRefactor framework [48] successfully eliminated 89% of test smells by combining domain-specific language (DSL) with CoT prompting.",
    "Other studies confirm that LLMs can be leveraged to automatically refactor obscure tests generated by traditional tools (e.g., EvoSuite) into maintainable code featuring meaningful variable names and comments [34,51]."
